            <section class="mb-5">
                <p>
                    Metacognition is self-awareness about thinking. It involves recognising underlying assumptions,
                    spotting patterns in how conclusions are formed, and understanding the limits of what can be
                    inferred from available information. Strong metacognitive skills help people interpret arguments
                    more carefully, avoid common reasoning traps, and better understand both their own judgements
                    and those of others (Flavell, 1979; Dunlosky &amp; Metcalfe, 2009).
                </p>
                <p>
                    This ability does not develop automatically. When answers and explanations are readily available,
                    people may spend less time reflecting on how they reached a conclusion or why a line of reasoning
                    feels convincing. Exercises that ask learners to identify hidden assumptions, evaluate evidence,
                    or reason about what someone else can know encourage this kind of reflective awareness. Regular
                    engagement with such tasks can help maintain a more thoughtful, self-aware approach to reasoning
                    in everyday decisions and discussions (Kuhn, 1999; Nelson &amp; Narens, 1990).
                </p>
            </section>

